00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:21.640
Let me just pick up where we
left off on Friday.

00:00:21.640 --> 00:00:26.200
And that is we were talking
about some of the physical and

00:00:26.200 --> 00:00:30.840
chemical properties of the
elements as we go across or down

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:35.303
the Periodic Table.
And one of those properties

00:00:35.303 --> 00:00:39.740
that we were talking about was
the electron affinity,

00:00:39.740 --> 00:00:43.153
which I defined for shorthand
just as EA.

00:00:43.153 --> 00:00:45.542
And we saw that,
for example,

00:00:45.542 --> 00:00:49.894
if we add an electron to
chlorine to make the anion,

00:00:49.894 --> 00:00:54.501
chlorine minus,
that there is an energy change

00:00:54.501 --> 00:01:00.139
associated with that reaction.
And that energy change was

00:01:00.139 --> 00:01:04.089
minus 349 kilojoules.
And what we saw is that the

00:01:04.089 --> 00:01:08.945
electron affinity is defined as
the negative of this energy.

00:01:08.945 --> 00:01:13.306
So the electron affinity,
here, is minus this delta E.

00:01:13.306 --> 00:01:18.408
So if you have a reaction that
you write with something plus an

00:01:18.408 --> 00:01:23.346
electron to give the anion here,
the change in that energy is

00:01:23.346 --> 00:01:28.119
this, in the case of chlorine,
but the electron affinity is

00:01:28.119 --> 00:01:31.894
defined as minus that.
All right.

00:01:31.894 --> 00:01:36.277
So chlorine we say has an
electron affinity of 349

00:01:36.277 --> 00:01:39.766
kilojoules per mole.
And it is positive.

00:01:39.766 --> 00:01:44.686
Now, unlike the ionization
energy, the electron affinity

00:01:44.686 --> 00:01:47.191
can be negative.
For example,

00:01:47.191 --> 00:01:52.380
if you take nitrogen and you
try to stick an electron on it

00:01:52.380 --> 00:01:57.031
to make N minus,
delta E for this reaction is

00:01:57.031 --> 00:02:01.643
positive.
When delta E is positive it

00:02:01.643 --> 00:02:04.777
means, of course,
that the anion,

00:02:04.777 --> 00:02:08.694
the product here,
is less stable than the

00:02:08.694 --> 00:02:14.569
reactant or the neutral atom.
You cannot put an electron onto

00:02:14.569 --> 00:02:17.409
nitrogen.
It won't stay there.

00:02:17.409 --> 00:02:20.836
It will fall apart.
It is not bound.

00:02:20.836 --> 00:02:23.676
And, therefore,
nitrogen here,

00:02:23.676 --> 00:02:28.572
the electron affinity of a
nitrogen atom is minus 7

00:02:28.572 --> 00:02:34.058
kilojoules per mole.
So you can have a negative

00:02:34.058 --> 00:02:37.542
electron affinity.
So nitrogen has a negative

00:02:37.542 --> 00:02:41.185
electron affinity.
And you can understand it in

00:02:41.185 --> 00:02:44.748
terms of the electronic
structure of nitrogen.

00:02:44.748 --> 00:02:49.104
If you draw the states of
nitrogen and put the electrons

00:02:49.104 --> 00:02:52.350
in the states here,
here is the electronic

00:02:52.350 --> 00:02:55.834
structure of nitrogen,
just nitrogen neutral.

00:02:55.834 --> 00:03:00.506
But now if you go and you try
to add another electron to the

00:03:00.506 --> 00:03:05.099
nitrogen, it's going to have to
go into one of these filled

00:03:05.099 --> 00:03:09.444
states.
There is a repulsion between

00:03:09.444 --> 00:03:13.722
these two electrons.
That repulsive interaction is

00:03:13.722 --> 00:03:18.436
large enough so that the
attractive interaction between

00:03:18.436 --> 00:03:23.674
the electrons and the nucleus is
not great enough to overcome

00:03:23.674 --> 00:03:29.000
that negative interaction,
that repulsive interaction.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.224
And, therefore,
the electron affinity here is

00:03:32.224 --> 00:03:36.475
negative or, in other words,
this delta E here is positive.

00:03:36.475 --> 00:03:40.286
So you can understand that in
terms of the electronic

00:03:40.286 --> 00:03:42.851
structure.
The other atoms that have

00:03:42.851 --> 00:03:46.368
negative electron affinities are
the inner gases.

00:03:46.368 --> 00:03:49.373
Here is a plot of the electron
affinities.

00:03:49.373 --> 00:03:53.770
Here are all the inner gases.
They all have negative electron

00:03:53.770 --> 00:03:58.021
affinities, because you're
trying to put an electron in the

00:03:58.021 --> 00:04:02.297
next shell.
That's a higher energy state.

00:04:02.297 --> 00:04:06.891
The charge on the nucleus is
not large enough to compensate

00:04:06.891 --> 00:04:10.534
for that extra energy to promote
that electron,

00:04:10.534 --> 00:04:14.336
to put that electron in that
higher energy state.

00:04:14.336 --> 00:04:17.425
All right.
So let's look at what happens

00:04:17.425 --> 00:04:21.702
here as we go across the
Periodic Table to the electron

00:04:21.702 --> 00:04:24.871
affinities.
As you go across the Periodic

00:04:24.871 --> 00:04:29.227
Table, the bottom line is,
in general, that the electron

00:04:29.227 --> 00:04:34.434
affinities increase.
They get larger as you go

00:04:34.434 --> 00:04:39.790
across the Periodic Table.
They get larger because the Z

00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:42.906
on the nucleus is getting
larger.

00:04:42.906 --> 00:04:47.093
The charge on the nucleus is
getting larger.

00:04:47.093 --> 00:04:52.352
When that charge gets larger,
the Coulombic interaction

00:04:52.352 --> 00:04:58.000
between the nucleus and the
electrons is greater.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.229
And if that's greater,
well, then the electron

00:05:01.229 --> 00:05:05.248
affinity here is going to go up.
And it's greater because

00:05:05.248 --> 00:05:09.698
remember, that potential energy
of interaction is minus Z times

00:05:09.698 --> 00:05:14.004
e, the charge on the nucleus
times Z over 4 pi 

00:05:14.004 --> 00:05:17.090
epsilon nought r.

00:05:17.090 --> 00:05:20.177
If Z is going up,
this interaction Coulombic

00:05:20.177 --> 00:05:23.622
attraction becomes greater.
But at the same time,

00:05:23.622 --> 00:05:28.000
we've got another parameter
here, and that's r.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.121
And r, as you go across the
Periodic Table,

00:05:31.121 --> 00:05:35.135
is remaining essentially
constant because you're in the

00:05:35.135 --> 00:05:38.256
same shell.
So if you're in the same shell,

00:05:38.256 --> 00:05:41.824
r is about constant.
And so the only thing really

00:05:41.824 --> 00:05:44.945
changing is Z.
And so the electron affinity

00:05:44.945 --> 00:05:47.250
goes up.
The same reason why the

00:05:47.250 --> 00:05:51.709
ionization energy goes up as we
go across the Periodic Table,

00:05:51.709 --> 00:05:54.608
as we talked about last time.
All right.

00:05:54.608 --> 00:05:58.175
But now, in general,
let's look at going down the

00:05:58.175 --> 00:06:02.111
Periodic Table here.
All right.

00:06:02.111 --> 00:06:04.111
Fluorine.
Chlorine.

00:06:04.111 --> 00:06:05.777
Bromine.
Iodine.

00:06:05.777 --> 00:06:11.000
Well, in general,
the electron affinity actually

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:15.555
goes down.
And the electron affinity there

00:06:15.555 --> 00:06:21.111
goes down because r is,
in general, getting larger.

00:06:21.111 --> 00:06:27.111
You're putting electrons in
shells that are further and

00:06:27.111 --> 00:06:32.403
further away.
Z is also getting larger,

00:06:32.403 --> 00:06:35.576
but not fast enough compared to
r.

00:06:35.576 --> 00:06:39.615
So, in general,
that electron affinity goes

00:06:39.615 --> 00:06:43.076
down.
There are always some glitches,

00:06:43.076 --> 00:06:46.153
but in general that is the
trend.

00:06:46.153 --> 00:06:49.230
Okay.
So then, the other property

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:55.000
that I wanted to talk about is
the atomic radius.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.404
And the atomic radius here is
plotted on the side.

00:07:05.404 --> 00:07:11.801
And let's look at what happens
as we go across the Periodic

00:07:11.801 --> 00:07:14.889
Table here.
Well, in general,

00:07:14.889 --> 00:07:20.955
as we go across the Periodic
Table, the atomic radius is

00:07:20.955 --> 00:07:25.588
going down.
The atomic radius is going down

00:07:25.588 --> 00:07:30.000
because, again,
Z is going up.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.782
The charge on the nucleus is
getting larger,

00:07:33.782 --> 00:07:38.445
meaning that attractive
interaction is getting larger,

00:07:38.445 --> 00:07:42.756
meaning that those electrons
are pulled in closer.

00:07:42.756 --> 00:07:46.803
Now, as you go across the
Periodic Table again,

00:07:46.803 --> 00:07:50.058
your r is remaining,
roughly speaking,

00:07:50.058 --> 00:07:55.513
the same, in the sense that the
electrons are in the same shell

00:07:55.513 --> 00:08:00.000
with the same principle quantum
number.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:03.221
So, in general,
that's remaining the same.

00:08:03.221 --> 00:08:07.385
So that's not changing.
It's Z that is changing as you

00:08:07.385 --> 00:08:11.707
go across the Periodic Table.
And that is the dominating

00:08:11.707 --> 00:08:15.792
factor, the change in Z.
The change in Z brings those

00:08:15.792 --> 00:08:18.542
electrons in closer.
And, therefore,

00:08:18.542 --> 00:08:23.100
the radius actually goes down.
And then what about down the

00:08:23.100 --> 00:08:25.378
Periodic Table,
down a column?

00:08:25.378 --> 00:08:28.992
Well, in this case,
as you go down the Periodic

00:08:28.992 --> 00:08:33.000
Table, again,
Z is also increasing.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:38.276
But it's r that is changing
faster than Z because you're

00:08:38.276 --> 00:08:42.785
having electrons in shells that,
on the average,

00:08:42.785 --> 00:08:47.007
are a farther distance away
from the nucleus.

00:08:47.007 --> 00:08:52.380
And that is increasing more
rapidly than Z is increasing,

00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:56.313
so, therefore,
this radius here is getting

00:08:56.313 --> 00:08:59.000
larger.
All right.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.837
So those are the three big
trends across the Periodic Table

00:09:04.837 --> 00:09:09.970
that you should know.
Ionization energy and electron

00:09:09.970 --> 00:09:15.204
affinity increase as you go
across, radius decreased.

00:09:15.204 --> 00:09:21.444
Ionization energy and electron
affinity decrease as you go down

00:09:21.444 --> 00:09:27.081
a column, radius increases.
That is something that you do

00:09:27.081 --> 00:09:30.000
need to know.
Okay.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:35.503
Now there is one other concept
or quantity that I want to make

00:09:35.503 --> 00:09:39.654
you familiar with,
and that is something called

00:09:39.654 --> 00:09:42.000
the electronegativity.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.124
And the electronegativity is
really an empirical concept.

00:09:53.124 --> 00:09:57.882
We're going to use the
definition gave by Mulliken in

00:09:57.882 --> 00:10:02.000
1934, as opposed to Pauling's
definition.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:06.767
Mulliken's definition is a
little bit more straightforward.

00:10:06.767 --> 00:10:10.958
And the electronegativity is
often just labeled chi,

00:10:10.958 --> 00:10:15.561
and it is given by one-half
times the quantity ionization

00:10:15.561 --> 00:10:20.082
energy plus the electron
affinity.

00:10:20.082 --> 00:10:24.931
That is out electronegativity.
So the electronegativity here

00:10:24.931 --> 00:10:29.534
is kind of some average of the
ionization energy plus the

00:10:29.534 --> 00:10:34.792
electron affinity.
The electronegativity is some

00:10:34.792 --> 00:10:40.666
measure of the tendency of an
atom to accept an electron or to

00:10:40.666 --> 00:10:45.192
donate electrons.
So if the electronegativity of

00:10:45.192 --> 00:10:49.718
an atom is high that's a good
electron acceptor.

00:10:49.718 --> 00:10:54.340
If the electronegativity of an
atom is low, well,

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:59.147
that's a good electron donor.
For example,

00:10:59.147 --> 00:11:04.217
if you look at the Periodic
Table here and you look at

00:11:04.217 --> 00:11:08.713
electronegativities,
the elements that have high

00:11:08.713 --> 00:11:11.965
electronegativities,
high chi here,

00:11:11.965 --> 00:11:15.217
are in the upper right-hand
corner.

00:11:15.217 --> 00:11:20.382
These atoms have large
electronegativities because they

00:11:20.382 --> 00:11:25.930
have high electron affinities
and high ionization energies.

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:31.000
These atoms are good electron
acceptors.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:35.270
They're good electron acceptors
because their electron affinity

00:11:35.270 --> 00:11:37.819
is high.
The change in the energy when

00:11:37.819 --> 00:11:41.745
you add an electron is very
large and negative meaning the

00:11:41.745 --> 00:11:44.983
electron affinity is high.
They're good electron

00:11:44.983 --> 00:11:47.463
acceptors.
They're also good electron

00:11:47.463 --> 00:11:50.838
acceptors because their
ionization energy is high.

00:11:50.838 --> 00:11:54.076
It is difficult.
You have to put a lot of energy

00:11:54.076 --> 00:11:56.693
into the system to remove the
electron.

00:11:56.693 --> 00:12:00.000
They're good electron
acceptors.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.872
On the other hand,
if you look at the elements

00:12:03.872 --> 00:12:09.293
down here in the left-hand lower
corner, these elements have low

00:12:09.293 --> 00:12:10.756
chi.
They have low

00:12:10.756 --> 00:12:14.715
electronegativities.
They are not good electron

00:12:14.715 --> 00:12:18.157
acceptors.
Their electron affinity is low

00:12:18.157 --> 00:12:21.083
and their ionization energy is
low.

00:12:21.083 --> 00:12:25.127
So these elements here are good
electron donors.

00:12:25.127 --> 00:12:31.538
Their ionization energy is low.
You don't have to put in as

00:12:31.538 --> 00:12:37.179
much energy to pull an electron
off as you do for some of the

00:12:37.179 --> 00:12:41.504
other elements.
They have low ionization energy

00:12:41.504 --> 00:12:44.888
and low electron affinity.
All right.

00:12:44.888 --> 00:12:50.341
So you can already suspect that
some of the strongest ionic

00:12:50.341 --> 00:12:55.794
bonds are going to be made
between those elements with high

00:12:55.794 --> 00:13:02.000
electronegativity and those with
low electronegativity.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.636
Because in an ionic bond,
as we're going to talk about,

00:13:06.636 --> 00:13:10.242
there is this unequal sharing
of electrons.

00:13:10.242 --> 00:13:15.136
So strong ionize bonds are
typically made between elements

00:13:15.136 --> 00:13:18.914
of high electronegativity and
elements of low

00:13:18.914 --> 00:13:21.318
electronegativity.
All right.

00:13:21.318 --> 00:13:26.297
And then finally one other
concept, or one other definition

00:13:26.297 --> 00:13:31.535
that I just wanted to make sure
everybody was on the same page

00:13:31.535 --> 00:13:36.000
with is this term here,
isoelectronic.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:41.672
Isoelectronic means having the
same electron structure,

00:13:41.672 --> 00:13:45.453
having the same electronic
structure.

00:13:45.453 --> 00:13:51.441
All of these atoms and ions
have the 1s 2 2s 2 2p 6

00:13:51.441 --> 00:13:56.483
electron structure.
So nitrogen here.

00:13:56.483 --> 00:14:01.000
Nitrogen has added three
electrons.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:06.837
That makes it minus three to
get this electronic structure.

00:14:06.837 --> 00:14:11.870
Aluminum has pulled three
electrons off to get this

00:14:11.870 --> 00:14:16.399
electronic structure.
These are isoelectronic.

00:14:16.399 --> 00:14:22.136
And typically the common ions
that are found in nature are

00:14:22.136 --> 00:14:26.967
ions that have this octet,
this inner gas kind of

00:14:26.967 --> 00:14:32.000
structure to it like the neon
structure.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.895
So, for example,
typically you will see a

00:14:34.895 --> 00:14:37.285
nitrogen minus three
ion.

00:14:37.285 --> 00:14:41.122
You won't see nitrogen minus
two because that

00:14:41.122 --> 00:14:44.018
doesn't have the inner gas
configuration.

00:14:44.018 --> 00:14:48.072
You will see oxygen minus two,
but you won't see

00:14:48.072 --> 00:14:52.054
oxygen minus one,
because that doesn't have the

00:14:52.054 --> 00:14:54.515
inner gas configuration.
All right.

00:14:54.515 --> 00:14:58.714
So common ions in nature are
ions that have either added or

00:14:58.714 --> 00:15:04.000
removed electrons to obtain that
inner gas configuration.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.805
Okay.
So those were a little bit of

00:15:06.805 --> 00:15:10.848
the odds and ends,
that I wanted to just make sure

00:15:10.848 --> 00:15:14.478
that we all understood each
other about them.

00:15:14.478 --> 00:15:19.099
And now what we're going to do
is we're going to move on,

00:15:19.099 --> 00:15:23.306
and we're actually going to
start talking about what

00:15:23.306 --> 00:15:27.514
chemistry is all about.
And that is the formation of

00:15:27.514 --> 00:15:31.659
bonds.
We're going to take these atoms

00:15:31.659 --> 00:15:37.063
now and we're going to put them
together and we're going to make

00:15:37.063 --> 00:15:41.352
some chemical bonds.
So I am going to start to talk

00:15:41.352 --> 00:15:46.843
about this just in terms of what
are the fundamental interactions

00:15:46.843 --> 00:15:50.274
that are taking place in a
chemical bond.

00:15:50.274 --> 00:15:55.078
So that's what I will do for
most of the rest of the hour

00:15:55.078 --> 00:16:00.053
today, is to talk about those
fundamental interactions that

00:16:00.053 --> 00:16:04.000
are common to all chemical
bonds.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.491
And then at the end of the
hour, I'm going to tell you

00:16:08.491 --> 00:16:13.661
about one very simple model for
bonding, which are these Lewis

00:16:13.661 --> 00:16:16.881
diagrams.
And then in the next few days

00:16:16.881 --> 00:16:20.779
we will look at some more
sophisticated models.

00:16:20.779 --> 00:16:25.440
We'll look at molecular orbital
theory and we'll look at

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:29.000
hybridization.
That is the plan.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.057
So today, just the elementary
principles behind chemical

00:16:34.057 --> 00:16:38.471
bonds, the elementary
interactions and a start on

00:16:38.471 --> 00:16:41.873
Lewis structures.
Let's take hydrogen.

00:16:41.873 --> 00:16:46.011
That is going to be our
prototypical molecule.

00:16:46.011 --> 00:16:50.425
If we have two hydrogen atoms
that are far apart,

00:16:50.425 --> 00:16:54.011
well, we have the hydrogen
nucleus here,

00:16:54.011 --> 00:16:58.701
which is positive and its
electron, which we'll call

00:16:58.701 --> 00:17:03.494
electron A.
And they're sort of attached.

00:17:03.494 --> 00:17:07.021
And way out here is another
hydrogen atom.

00:17:07.021 --> 00:17:11.150
Here is the nucleus and its
electron, electron B.

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:15.881
And so in the separated atom
limit, the interaction that

00:17:15.881 --> 00:17:19.666
we've got is the
electron-nuclear attraction.

00:17:19.666 --> 00:17:24.569
This electron is attracted to
this nucleus and vice versa.

00:17:24.569 --> 00:17:29.387
It's that electron-nuclear
attraction that is operable in

00:17:29.387 --> 00:17:35.304
both of these hydrogen atoms.
But now, as these two atoms

00:17:35.304 --> 00:17:39.317
come closer together,
well, this nucleus here is

00:17:39.317 --> 00:17:43.756
bringing its electron along,
and this nucleus here is

00:17:43.756 --> 00:17:47.853
bringing its electron along.
But what happens is,

00:17:47.853 --> 00:17:52.548
as they get closer together,
this electron that was only

00:17:52.548 --> 00:17:56.817
attracted to this nucleus,
nucleus A, now begins to

00:17:56.817 --> 00:18:01.000
experience an attraction to
nucleus B.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.681
And this electron that was
attached only to nucleus B

00:18:05.681 --> 00:18:10.813
experiences an attractive
interaction here with nucleus A.

00:18:10.813 --> 00:18:15.495
And it is that mutual
attraction of the electrons for

00:18:15.495 --> 00:18:21.257
both nuclei that actually is the
force, the energy of interaction

00:18:21.257 --> 00:18:25.938
that brings the two nuclei
