00:39:17.824 --> 00:39:20.599
repulsion between these two
electrons.

00:39:20.599 --> 00:39:26.215
How can I estimate that?
Well, experimentally I can

00:39:26.215 --> 00:39:32.522
estimate that by taking the
first ionization energy,

00:39:32.522 --> 00:39:37.346
making that minus,
plus minus the second

00:39:37.346 --> 00:39:43.406
ionization energy.
That will be my total energy of

00:39:43.406 --> 00:39:49.466
interaction as far as the
electrons are concerned.

00:39:49.466 --> 00:39:58.000
So I go and I look up the first
ionization energy of helium.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:03.514
Remember the first ionization
energy was the energy required

00:40:03.514 --> 00:40:08.186
to pull off the first electron?
I find that number.

00:40:08.186 --> 00:40:12.859
The binding energy is minus
that ionization energy,

00:40:12.859 --> 00:40:16.691
so that's why I put that minus
sign there.

00:40:16.691 --> 00:40:20.429
I do that, and that removes one
electron.

00:40:20.429 --> 00:40:25.757
And now, I want to know how
much is this electron bound to

00:40:25.757 --> 00:40:31.223
the nucleus.
I go up and I look up my second

00:40:31.223 --> 00:40:37.253
ionization energy for helium,
where I solve the SchrÃ¶dinger

00:40:37.253 --> 00:40:40.581
equation for a one electron
atom.

00:40:40.581 --> 00:40:44.948
I look that up.
That's minus the ionization

00:40:44.948 --> 00:40:48.587
energy.
It turns out that the sum of

00:40:48.587 --> 00:40:53.058
those two is minus 7622
kilojoules per mole.

00:40:53.058 --> 00:40:58.464
Does this make sense?
The electron-nuclear attraction

00:40:58.464 --> 00:41:04.223
plus the repulsion --
I cannot separate those two

00:41:04.223 --> 00:41:08.752
terms, but I know what they are
experimentally as a sum,

00:41:08.752 --> 00:41:13.776
because I go and I measure how
much energy is required to pull

00:41:13.776 --> 00:41:18.058
the first electron off,
add it to the energy required

00:41:18.058 --> 00:41:22.176
to pull the second electron off.
That's totally the

00:41:22.176 --> 00:41:27.447
electron-nuclear attraction plus
the electron-electron repulsion.

00:41:27.447 --> 00:41:33.783
That's what that is.
And I have to make it negative

00:41:33.783 --> 00:41:41.099
because the binding energy,
the energy interaction is minus

00:41:41.099 --> 00:41:47.531
the ionization energy.
So way over here on this plot

00:41:47.531 --> 00:41:52.198
I've got another point for r
equals 0.

00:41:52.198 --> 00:41:58.000
That is minus 7622 kilojoules
per mole.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:02.252
And so now what I'm going to do
is I am going to just draw a

00:42:02.252 --> 00:42:06.360
line here between the two.
I just interpolate it because I

00:42:06.360 --> 00:42:10.324
don't know what else to do.
I don't know how to get that

00:42:10.324 --> 00:42:14.504
energy of interaction in a
simple way as a function of r in

00:42:14.504 --> 00:42:17.675
any other way.
But now, what I've got are the

00:42:17.675 --> 00:42:19.765
three components.
Here is one,

00:42:19.765 --> 00:42:23.009
the r dependence.
Here is my approximation for

00:42:23.009 --> 00:42:26.972
the r dependence of the sum of
the other two components.

00:42:26.972 --> 00:42:32.188
I am going to add them up.
Because my total energy of

00:42:32.188 --> 00:42:35.977
interaction I said was the sum
of those three.

00:42:35.977 --> 00:42:40.354
And when I add them up,
well, what I am going to get,

00:42:40.354 --> 00:42:44.563
if I add this curve to that
curve, I'm going to get

00:42:44.563 --> 00:42:49.783
something that looks like that.
This is going to bring it down.

00:42:49.783 --> 00:42:53.823
This goes to infinity,
so this will go high up to

00:42:53.823 --> 00:42:57.443
infinity here.
I am going to get a potential

00:42:57.443 --> 00:43:03.000
energy of interaction that looks
something like that.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:09.708
The point of all of this was to
illustrate that a chemical bond

00:43:09.708 --> 00:43:15.876
is really a result of the
competition between the electron

00:43:15.876 --> 00:43:20.421
interactions.
The electron interactions are

00:43:20.421 --> 00:43:25.940
this green line here.
It's a competition between the

00:43:25.940 --> 00:43:32.000
electron interactions,
which is always negative.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:38.053
Even though you have an
electron-electron repulsion

00:43:38.053 --> 00:43:44.955
here, which is a repulsive
interaction, the overall energy

00:43:44.955 --> 00:43:50.161
of interaction is negative.
It's attractive.

00:43:50.161 --> 00:43:55.973
The electron interactions
overall are attractive.

00:43:55.973 --> 00:44:01.558
They're negative.
So this chemical bond is a

00:44:01.558 --> 00:44:05.986
competition between the electron
interactions,

00:44:05.986 --> 00:44:10.316
which are attractive,
and the nuclear-nuclear

00:44:10.316 --> 00:44:13.859
repulsion, which is always
repulsive.

00:44:13.859 --> 00:44:18.484
This was always positive.
It's always repulsive.

00:44:18.484 --> 00:44:23.797
And what you can see here is
that there is some optimal

00:44:23.797 --> 00:44:29.702
distance which ends up being the
bond length, where the total

00:44:29.702 --> 00:44:36.000
energy of interaction is a
maximum negative number.

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:40.761
Where the total energy of
interaction is the greatest.

00:44:40.761 --> 00:44:44.714
In other words,
what you have to do is you're

00:44:44.714 --> 00:44:50.195
going to make a chemical bond.
You have to bring the two atoms

00:44:50.195 --> 00:44:54.777
in close enough so that the
electron attractions are

00:44:54.777 --> 00:44:59.000
present, which bring the two
nuclei in.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:04.425
But you cannot press them so
close together such that the

00:45:04.425 --> 00:45:10.043
nuclear repulsions take over.
So there is some intermediate

00:45:10.043 --> 00:45:15.371
distance here where you have
enough electron attraction,

00:45:15.371 --> 00:45:20.990
but you don't push them so
close that the nuclear repulsion

00:45:20.990 --> 00:45:25.059
takes over.
And it is that optimal distance

00:45:25.059 --> 00:45:30.000
here that is the equilibrium
bond length.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:36.617
Now, there is one other very
important point.

00:45:36.617 --> 00:45:45.191
And that is that what we often
do is we shift this zero of

00:45:45.191 --> 00:45:51.357
energy when we talk about a
chemical bond.

00:45:51.357 --> 00:45:59.930
This zero of energy right now
is 2624 kilojoules above the

00:45:59.930 --> 00:46:07.000
energy of the separated hydrogen
atoms.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:11.616
But we already saw that this
energy of interaction is the

00:46:11.616 --> 00:46:16.562
energy of interaction between
the electron and the nucleus in

00:46:16.562 --> 00:46:19.283
the separated hydrogen atom
limit.

00:46:19.283 --> 00:46:23.982
When we talk about a chemical
bond, we really want to know

00:46:23.982 --> 00:46:28.928
what the energy of interaction
between the two hydrogen atoms

00:46:28.928 --> 00:46:32.761
is.
And so it is useful for us to

00:46:32.761 --> 00:46:38.571
take for us to take this zero of
energy here and just shift it

00:46:38.571 --> 00:46:43.333
down and set it here,
make this the zero of energy.

00:46:43.333 --> 00:46:48.666
Now our zero of energy is when
the two hydrogen atoms are

00:46:48.666 --> 00:46:53.809
separated from each other.
That is just the convention.

00:46:53.809 --> 00:46:59.047
It is often useful to talk
about chemical bonds when you

00:46:59.047 --> 00:47:04.281
set the two atoms --
When they are far apart,

00:47:04.281 --> 00:47:09.223
and you set that energy of
interaction equal to zero.

00:47:09.223 --> 00:47:10.623
See you on Wednesday.

